article.headline: McGrady misses second straight game
article.linkText: Frank answers: Nets 6-0 under new coach
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The New Jersey Nets are proving that Rod Thorn made the right decision by firing Byron Scott and hiring Lawrence Frank. Jason Kidd had 18 points, 13 assists, six rebounds and a 3-pointer that cracked the 100-point mark at the end of third quarter, leading the Nets to 120-99 win over the Orlando Magic on Friday night. The victory was the Nets' seventh straight, and their sixth in a row since Frank took over the two-time defending Eastern Conference champions less than two weeks ago. "You have to give him credit," veteran guard Lucious Harris said of Frank. "He has turned us around. He gave us a new focus. You have to give most of the credit to him. He has focused on small details every day, no matter how good we play." The six wins to start a coaching career are three shy of the NBA record shared by Kurt Rambis in 1998-99 with the Lakers and Buddy Jeannette with the Baltimore Bullets in 1947. As he has done after each win, the 33-year-old Frank gave all the credit to his players. "This is a very unique group," Frank said. "Not to demean anyone else in the NBA, I would find it hard to find in any other locker room the type of character we have and the oneness in the sense of having one agenda -- winning." This one was easy, as the Magic played without All-Star guard Tracy McGrady (back spasms) for the second straight game. The Nets' 120 points, 41 assists, 59.8 shooting percentage and 64 points in the paint were all season highs. The assist total was a league high, one more than Dallas had against New Orleans on Nov. 11. The margin of victory would have been a season high, except the Magic closed the gap in garbage time. "It doesn't stop, that's our motto this week," Kidd said. "The team is relaxed. It feels very confident. We have that swagger back as K-Mart (Kenyon Martin) mentioned and we are a little more serious now." Frank got contributions from everyone as New Jersey won by double digits for the seventh straight game Kerry Kittles made six of his first seven shots and scored 12 of his 17 points in the first quarter. Martin had 18 points and 15 rebounds in recording his fourth straight double-double. Richard Jefferson added 15 points and Aaron Williams took over for the injured Jason Collins early at center and had a season-high 17 points. Juwan Howard did his best to make up for McGrady's absence, matching his season-high with 24 points. Gordan Giricek and Rod Strickland added 15 points apiece for the Magic, who have lost five in a row and seven of eight. "We put up a fight for a half, but it wasn't for long," Strickland said. "They pretty much dominated us from the third quarter on." In the final 7.4 seconds of the third quarter with New Jersey ahead 99-74, the Nets inbounded the ball from the backcourt and Kidd milked the clock before picking it up and quickly advancing to the frontcourt. He pulled up at the top of the key and launched a 3-pointer that swished, bringing the fans to their feet. Kidd sat on the bench throughout the final quarter.

Game notes
Orlando is 0-4 this year and 8-14 overall with McGrady sidelined. ... Martin actually scored another basket, deflecting an Orlando pass into his own basket in the third quarter. ... New Jersey has won 21 of 29, 13 of its last 15 at home and is 12-2 against Atlantic Division opponents. ... New Jersey is 3-0 vs. Magic this year, outscoring them 162-108 in the paint. ... Orlando is 4-22 when it allows 100 or more points. ... The game was played despite a constant leak from the roof caused by day-long rain.
